[normal]SECTION 3[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Business Finance initiatives [bold]in [bold]Northern Ireland[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Better Business Finance[bold]Better Business Finance (BBF) provides impartial information and support to business customers looking to raise finance. The BBF
[normal] is supported by the BBA in conjunction with some of our members and has been created to bring to life the recommendations of the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Business 
[normal]Finance Taskforce
[normal]. The BBF has three core themes at its heart: improving customer relationships; improving access to finance;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]as well as
[normal] improving information and transparency. It
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]includes supporting businesses through 
[normal]mentoring; 
[normal]the introduction of an 
[normal]independently monitored appeals process for finance applications and providing guidance to UK businesses on how to export abroad or pitch to a bank when seeking finance. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The BBF and its initiatives are gaining good traction with businesses generally but 
[normal]we acknowledge awareness of the mentoring and appeals support in Northern Ireland, as well as the support tools available for businesses such as mentorsme.co.uk, betterbusinessfinance.co.uk and businessfinanceforyou.co.uk, are not as extensive as we would 
[normal]have hoped. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To this end, we are working with the banks and the Northern Ireland Chambers of Commerce upon how we can further invigorate the mentoring scheme and with Professor Russel Griggs, with the CBI, and more generally the Ulster Business School, up
[normal]on how the appeals process and support tools are more widely known. Further detail
[normal]s
[normal] are 
[normal]outlined below
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Awareness Raising[bold]One of the key matters that the SME Finance Monitor 
[normal](SMEFf) 
[normal]highlights is the 
[normal]‘i
[normal]ndirect discouragement
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]a 
[normal]business to 
[normal]approach its bank 
[normal]to discuss 
[normal]its
[normal] finance need
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It 
[normal]i
[normal]s important that all parties
[normal]:
[normal] banks; business groups; government
[normal],
[normal] work together in 
[normal]building
[normal] confidence and 
[normal]promoting 
[normal]the support that is available to businesses. To this end the BBA is working with the N
[normal]o
[normal]rthern Ireland banks 
[normal]and business groups on  a series 
[normal]of
[normal] activities to raise awareness through, inter alia:  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Alongside the Better Business Finance Initiatives, the banks continue to work hard upon the deployment of the national UK Enterprise Finance Guarantee
[normal] (EFG) Scheme and Funding for Lending Scheme (FLS).  Both of these Schemes are positive initiatives seeking to support business, with EF
[normal]G
[normal] targeted at helping businesses with a lack of security and FLS seeking to ensure credit is more affordable for custome
[normal]rs. These schemes have had positive impact 
[normal]in Northern Ireland 
[normal]and the banks will continue to work closely with policy makers to ensure their optimal structure for the local Northern Ireland market. Progress of the schemes of course also depends on levels 
[normal]of credit demand which remain subdued.   
[normal]In addition
[normal],
[normal] the BBA with the major banks continues to review ways in which the banking industry can support and develop alternative finance options for business. This includes the establishment of the £2.5bn 
[normal]Busin[bold]ess Growth Fund[bold] 
[normal]in 2011 
[normal]which 
[normal]was
[normal] set up 
[normal]by the major UK banks as part of the commitments made under the Business Finance Taskforce to provide long term patient capital for growing SMEs. Now operating out of 
[normal]7
[normal] 
[normal]locations the BGF has invested
[normal] in the UK
[normal] over GBP 
[normal]150
[normal]m in growing businesses. The BGF 
[normal]continues to work
[normal] 
[normal]with business groups and banks in Northern Ireland, as regards 
[normal]to 
[normal]opportunities there
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]BBA is pleased
[normal] 
[normal]to see
[normal] the number of initiatives, presentations and meetings taking place to help buil
[normal]d a 
[normal]pipeline in Northern Ireland
[normal] across
[normal] 
[normal]a range of sectors
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The BBA has also recently entered into a strategic partnership with the UK Business Angels Association to help business gain greater understanding of the benefits and options from angel investors 
[normal]and is currently working on the rollout of a referral programme, whereby in instances where bank finance is not appropriate
[normal],
[normal] the business has the option to be referred by the bank to a local community development finance provider. 
[normal]L
[normal]ater this year
[normal] the BBA w
[normal]ill
[normal] be assessing how such a programme can be expanded to Northern Ireland
[normal].
[normal]    
